{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511325"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:41:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:41:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11741"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11741"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.48,0.03,0.39,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52060"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4354"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11741"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37376"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2496"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7905"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8489"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44588"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52060"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of increasing breathlessness. He has no other cardiorespiratory symptoms. His symptoms have started to interfere with his job at a quarry. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 15 pack-year smoking history. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Chest examination reveals dullness to percussion at the left base with reduced breath sounds. A chest X-ray is taken (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pleural biopsy","Pleural aspiration","Repeat chest X-ray in three weeks","CT chest","ECG"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this case of a small unilateral pleural effusion, the most appropriate next step is a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest\u003C/strong\u003E. This imaging modality provides detailed information about the lung parenchyma. CT can help identify possible underlying malignancies, masses, or endobronchial pathology that may not be visible on a plain chest X-ray. Additionally, it allows for cross-sectional imaging of the pleura to assess for nodularity or thickening, and can help differentiate between intrathoracic and subdiaphragmatic causes of the effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleural aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for larger effusions or if a small pleural effusion does not self-resolve. In this case, it would be premature to perform aspiration before obtaining more detailed imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeating a chest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E in three weeks could potentially miss an underlying malignancy and delay diagnosis. Given the patient\u0027s symptoms and risk factors (smoking history, occupational exposure), a more thorough investigation is warranted at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E might be useful if there was suspicion of pericarditis or pulmonary embolism, but the clinical presentation does not strongly suggest these conditions. Therefore, it is not the most appropriate next step in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epleural biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that can be useful in evaluating the underlying cause of an effusion, particularly an exudative effusion. However, it is not typically performed as an initial step and should be considered only after less invasive investigations have been completed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter the CT chest, the next step would likely be a pleural ultrasound to assess for pleural nodularity, thickening, and the safety of potential thoracocentesis. If deemed safe and necessary, a diagnostic thoracocentesis might then be performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that the patient\u0027s occupation in a quarry may be a risk factor for pneumoconiosis, such as silicosis. This occupational exposure should be considered in the differential diagnosis and further evaluated with the CT chest.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["CT chest is the most appropriate initial investigation for a small unilateral pleural effusion to evaluate underlying causes and assess lung parenchyma.","Pleural ultrasound is the best imaging modality to assess pleural nodularity, thickening, and safety of thoracocentesis.","Occupational exposure in quarry work may be a risk factor for pneumoconiosis such as silicosis."],"references":["Maskell NA, Butland RJ. BTS guidelines for the investigation of a unilateral pleural effusion in adults. Thorax. 2003;58(Suppl 2):ii8\u2013ii17. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1766019/pdf/v058p00ii8.pdf","Karkhanis VS, Joshi JM. Pleural effusion: diagnosis, treatment, and management. Open Access Emerg Med. 2012 Jun 22;4:31-52. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27147861/","Baba Y. Pleural effusion In: Radiopedia [online]. 2023. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/pleural-effusion"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37376"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11741"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20374"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20374"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xjtULqydSp4FJN8yslsNGEh7sJf2fP.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xjtULqydSp4FJN8yslsNGEh7sJf2fP.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":558,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37376"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T10:51:07+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T10:52:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4354"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52060"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+1